r than from the farm down here.   Because if they had drawn the circle 3 kilometres from this steading down here it would have taken out our farm and 25 others in Alston Moor.  It would have finished Alston Moor off as livestock farming.  There was two ve
ts on the job and they couldn\rquote 
t agree what to do and in the end they got in get in touch with the chief vet and he decided to draw the 3 kilometres from up the road there and so that meant we were out of the 3 kilometre cull and that made us feel slightly b
etter.  We still thinking it was in the valley and the way it was travelling it was inevitable we would get it.  
\par 
\par As time went it on you felt as if you were going to avoid this.  Because It went down the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname PlaceName}}Eden{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname PlaceType}}Valley{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, it went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}Carlisle{\*\xmlclose}, it went along the Roman wall and it went down Wierdale from Walsingdon down the vale, it was in Teasdale from Middleton down that wa
y.  We thought if we survive this we will do very well.  We had the feeling all the time that maybe we were going to get away with this.
\par 
\par Then, it was in April, towards the end of April, my father and I were up at Blagon which is the hill farm were the sheep are and the sheep pens are and there is house up there.  In fact it is the house that }{\insrsid8726086 K}{\insrsid1328142 
 looked at, we were up there and the guy who lives there he had been down Alston just 100 yards down the road he came in the yard.  We were busy injecting these s
